snippet: The Continent’s championship soccer game will be between two German teams, and many observers see a link to the country’s economic approach.
abstract: Memo from Berlin; two German clubs, one from Dortmund in the Ruhr Valley and the other from Munich in deepest Bavaria, will face off for European soccer title in Champions League; many observers view dominance of sport by German teams as representative of Teutonic dominance that has emerged during long-running debt crisis.

byline.contributor: Chris Cottrell contributed reporting from Berlin, Elisabetta Povoledo from Rome, and Raphael Minder from Madrid.

lead_paragraph: The Continent’s championship soccer game will be between two German teams, and many observers see a link to the country’s economic approach.

headline.seo: Germany Extends Its Success to the Soccer Field
headline.main: One More Field Where the Continent Trails Germany
headline.print_headline: One More Field Where the Continent Trails Germany
